{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17588527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17588527"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:09:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:09:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15165"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15165"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.59,0.28,0,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7856"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61462"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7856"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15165"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46913"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3461"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8133"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19152"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19155"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19746"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61462"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of right upper quadrant pain. The pain is constant, radiates to her right shoulder, and is worse after meals. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft, apart from some tenderness localised to the right upper quadrant.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Computed tomography scan of the abdomen","Right upper quadrant ultrasound","Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography","Hepatobiliary iminodiacetic acid scan","Plain abdominal radiograph"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of acute cholecystitis, including constant right upper quadrant pain radiating to the shoulder (referred pain via the phrenic nerve), and an area of tenderness in the right upper quadrant.  In this setting, imaging is essential to confirm the diagnosis and assess for any possible complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight upper quadrant ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is the initial imaging modality of choice for suspected gallbladder pathology. It is readily available, non-invasive, does not involve radiation, and has high sensitivity for detecting gallstones and signs of cholecystitis such as gallbladder wall thickening and the presence of pericholecystic fluid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography scan\u003C/strong\u003E of the abdomen is not the first-line investigation for suspected gallbladder disease. While it may show gallbladder pathology, it involves radiation exposure and is less sensitive than ultrasound for detecting gallstones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography\u003C/strong\u003E provides detailed imaging of the biliary tree but is typically reserved for cases where ultrasound is inconclusive or when choledocholithiasis is suspected. It is not necessary as an initial investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatobiliary iminodiacetic acid scan\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful in confirming acute cholecystitis when ultrasound findings are equivocal, but it is not the first-line investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlain abdominal radiograph\u003C/strong\u003E has limited utility in evaluating gallbladder disease as only about 20% of gallstones are radio-opaque. It may be helpful if perforation is suspected but would not be the initial investigation of choice.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Right upper quadrant ultrasound is indicated for suspected biliary pathology including cholecystitis, cholelithiasis, and biliary obstruction.","Localised right upper quadrant tenderness is a key clinical finding suggesting acute cholecystitis.","Imaging should be guided by clinical findings rather than isolated physical examination signs."],"references":["Musana KA, Yale SH. Murphy\u0027s Sign. Clin Med Res. 2005 Aug;3(3):132. doi: 10.3121/cmr.3.3.132. PMID: 16160065; PMCID: PMC1237152.","Revzin MV, Scoutt LM, Garner JG, Moore CL. Right Upper Quadrant Pain: Ultrasound First! J Ultrasound Med. 2017 Oct;36(10):1975-1985. doi: 10.1002/jum.14274. Epub 2017 Jun 6. PMID: 28586152.","Spence SC, Teichgraeber D, Chandrasekhar C. Emergent right upper quadrant sonography. J Ultrasound Med. 2009 Apr;28(4):479-96. doi: 10.7863/jum.2009.28.4.479. PMID: 19321676."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46913"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15165"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/46913"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-15T16:14:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T16:14:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":